Linear and nonlinear regression

Preclinical and Clinical Data Analysis in Predictive Drug Discovery

2020-12-07

1 Background

You have received a dataset (see below) with all the information collected during a drug study of the new antimalarial drug AMP1050.

Malaria is a very serious infectious disease that often leads to death if the victim does not receive the right treatment. Malaria is spread by mosquitoes and the disease occurs mainly in tropical and subtropical parts of the world.7 Until the middle of the 20th century, however, malaria was also common in Europe, Russia (Soviet Union) and North America. In Sweden, the disease disappeared during the 1930s.6

Malaria is caused by parasites belonging to the genus Plasmodium. In humans, it is mainly P. falciparum and P. vivax which causes the disease, but there are also other species that can cause malaria.6 Virtually all deaths in malaria are caused by P. falciparum while P. vivax causes fever and great discomfort but rarely leads to death. Every year, around 220 million people worldwide are affected by malaria, and the World Health Organization (WHO) estimates that about 660,000 people died as a result of the disease in 2010.7

There is currently no 100% protection against malaria. During trips to malaria-affected areas, prophylactic drugs can be prescribed, but this type of treatment is rarely relevant for those who live and work in these areas. The need for new drugs to cure those affected by P. falciparum malaria is also high as the parasites have begun to develop resistance to existing drugs.

The antimalarial drugs available on the market today can be divided into two classes; long-acting drugs, which remain in the body and kill the malaria parasites for several weeks after the patient has taken the drug, and fast-acting drugs, which quickly and effectively kill many malaria parasites but which only remain in the body for a few hours after that that the patient has taken the medicine. To avoid the development of resistance, several antimalarial drugs are often given at the same time, in so-called combination treatments. The most common is that a long-acting antimalarial drug is given together with a fast-acting antimalarial drug.4 The fast-acting drug is usually an artimisinin derivative, and the fear that P. falciparum should develop resistance to artemisinin derivatives is large.2,7 Development of resistance to artemisinin derivatives has so far been reported from Cambodia and Thailand.1,3,5

2 Study

The pharmaceutical company Academic Malaria-Pharma has, after many years of research, developed a new fast-acting antimalarial drug. The drug, which has been given the working name AMP1050, has shown promising results in preclinical studies (animal studies) and Academic Malaria-Pharma has therefore received the go-ahead to test the drug on patients.

The clinical study was conducted in Uganda and a total of 30 individuals were recruited with P. falciparum malaria to the study. Information about all individuals was carefully documented. The study was a so-called parallel group study and the individuals were randomized to one of 4 study arms (10 individuals were randomized to study arm-1; 8 individuals were randomized to study arm-2; 5 individuals were randomized to study arm-3 and 7 individuals were randomized to study arm-4). All subjects were given combination therapy with piperakine (a long-acting antimalarial drug) and, either artemisinin or AMP1050. The subjects in study arm-1 received 500 mg artemisinin, the subjects in study arm-2 received 100 mg AMP1050, the subjects in study arm-3 received 250 mg AMP1050 and the subjects in study arm-4 received 500 mg AMP1050. During the study, several blood samples were taken from the individuals. The blood samples were analyzed and the number of parasites in the blood was measured as parasites/µL. Concentration of drugs in the blood samples was also analyzed, and the highest measured drug concentration was recorded for all individuals. The effect of the fast-acting drugs can be calculated as the difference between the number of parasites in the blood before the first dose and the number of parasites in the blood 6 hours after the first dose.

3 Dataset

Download, open, and look at the dataset. Each row in the dataset contains information about an individual, each column is a variable. Below is a list of the types of information that can be found in the various columns in the dataset.

Table 3.1: Information that can be found in the various columns in the dataset.
Colummn Explaination
id Identification number used instead of the individual’s name (or social security number) to keep the individual’s identity secret.
female The individual’s genetic gender (female = 1, male = 0).
height Individens kroppslängd i cm.
weight The individual’s body length in cm.
age The individual’s age in years.
drug Which drug the individual received (artemisinin = 1, AMP1050 = 2).
dose What dose of the drug (artemisinin or AMP1050) the individual received: 100, 250 or 500 mg.
cmax Highest drug concentration (ng / mL) measured in the individual’s blood samples.
parasite_0h The number of parasites (parasites / µL) that were measured in the blood sample that was taken just before the individual received his first drug dose.
parasite_6h The number of parasites (parasites / µL) measured in the blood sample taken 6 hours after the individual received his first drug dose.
temp_0h The measured body temperature (ºC) just before the individual receives their first drug dose.
temp_6h The measured body temperature (ºC) 6 hours after the individual received their first dose of drug.
study_arm The study arm to which the individual is randomized.

Which variable pairs have non-linear relationships?
  • Length and Gender

First we have to load the dataset to R (make sure your “working directory” is where Dataset.csv is located):

data <- read.csv("Dataset.csv")

For length and sex (first variable pairs) we can create a scatter plot with the following code. The result shows data, regression line and uncertainty around the line (95% confidence interval).

# install the ggplot2 library
if(!nzchar(system.file(package = "ggplot2"))) install.packages("ggplot2")

# load the ggplot2 library
library(ggplot2)

# make the plot
p1 <- ggplot(data=data, aes(x=female,y=height)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

# show the plot
p1

Then we can also get a more detailed analysis of the linear regression with the following code:

# evaluate the linear fit to data
fit_1 <- lm(height~female,data)

# summarize that fit to data
summary(fit_1)

Tip 1: When you are going to make scatter diagrams with Dos and/or Cmax, you should use data for individuals who received AMP1050.

Tip 2: The decrease in parasite levels is the difference in the number of parasites/µL blood at the beginning of the study compared to 6 hours after the first drug dose (Parasite 0h - Parasite 6h) and Decrease in temperature is the difference in body temperature at the beginning of the study compared to 6 hours after the first drug dose (Temp 0h - Temp 6h). What do the negative values in these calculations mean?

Tip 3: When you plot “Body temperature and parasite level in the blood”, then use that you have data for these at both 0 hours and 6 hours. First make a scatter plot for the variables at 0 hours and then another scatter plot for the variables at 6 hours.

Scatter diagram showing how the height covaries with sex. The regression equation shows that the average Ugandan man is 9.91 cm taller than the average Ugandan woman (the regression coefficient “Intercept”, b, is -9.91).

The coefficient of determination (“Multiple R-squatred”) shows that 28.4% of the variation in length between different individuals can be explained by the gender of the individuals (i.e. 71.6% of the variation in length is due to other things than that the individuals have different genders). The correlation coefficient (r) can be calculated by \(r=\sqrt {r ^ 2} =\pm 0.533\). Since the regression coefficient is negative, the correlation coefficient is also negative. A correlation coefficient of -0.533 means that there is a relatively weak, negative (linear) relationship between the variables length and gender (male = 0, female = 1).

  1. Regression analyses, i.e. hypothesis tests where it is examined whether there is any significant linear relationship between two (or more) variables, can easily be performed with built-in functions in R.

\(H_0\): \(b = 0\), there is no relationship between the variables, any observed relationship has arisen by chance.

\(H_1\): \(b \ne 0\), there is a relationship between the variables, any observed relationship has not arisen by chance (two-sided test).

You have all the information needed from the results of the lm () and summary () exercises. The results produced (automatically) in regression analyzes are extensive. A review of the most important parameters follows below.

You know the value of the \(R^2\) value (determination coefficient).

F-statistics indicate the p-value for the probability that the relationship observed between the variables has arisen by chance. If the p-value is below the selected significance level (0.05 if the significance level is 5%) then \(H_0\) is rejected. Which of the relationships in the regression analyzes are significant at the 5% significance level? Which relationships are significant at the 1% significance level?

You will also find calculated t-values and the corresponding p-values (Pr (> | t |)) for each regression parameter. Are all the p-values for the regression coefficient below the selected significance level?

Solution. The relationship between height and weight is significant at both 1% and 5% significance level (p-value: 0.0015). The relationship between age and weight is not significant at all (p-value: 0.98). The relationship between Cmax and the decrease in the number of parasites in the blood is significant at the 5% significance level but not at the 1% significance level (p-value: 0.040).


  1. A linear regression analysis can also analyze the relationship between more than two variables. In these cases, one examines how several different independent variables affect a dependent variable. Examine the relationship between height (independent variable 1), age (independent variable 2) and weight (dependent variable). Also examine how correlation terms effect the results.
fit_10 <- lm(weight~height+age,data)

  • Examine the p-values for the regression coefficients. Are any of the variables that have a significant relationship with weight (at the 5% significance level) when both variables are used to predict weight?

Solution. x-variable 1 (height) has a significant relationship with weight at both 1% and 5% significance level (p-value: 0.0012) but x-variable 2 (age) has no significant relationship with weight (p-value: 0.37). Note, however, that the p-value for the relationship between age and weight is significantly lower in the multiple regression analysis, as the relationship between height and weight is also included. This can also be seen in the value of the coefficient of determination which was 0.306 when only the height was used to predict the weight, 0.0000175 when only the age was used to predict the weight and 0.327 when both the height and the age were used to predict the weight. This means that height and age together explain more of the differences observed in weight than height does on its own, but the difference is not significant.

When a correlation term is added to the model then all model parameter are not different from zero according to the p-values. This can be interpreted as the addition of this extra correlation term makes the model over-parameterized, so no parameters can be estimated with enough precision.


  1. The decrease in parasite levels in the blood correlates with the maximum drug concentration for AMP1050, which we saw in above. The scatter plot shows that there is a clear covariation between the variables but that this covariation is not linear (the linear regression line does not go through the points at all). We will try to describe that covariation with a non-linear model.

First, we will try to get the parasite difference on a skale that varies less. Often you can do this with a log transformation of data.

data$log_par_delta <- log(data$parasite_0h) - log(data$parasite_6h)
data_AMP1050 <- subset(data, drug==2)

Then we can visualize this

It looks more linear with this transformation of data, but let’s try a non-linear fit with an \(E_{max}\) model:

Visualization of this model with uncertainty. First, we calculate confidence intervals on each x-value:

fit_to_plot <- ??? # Give a model fit that you want to use


get_pred_ci <- function(fit_to_plot){
  if(class(fit_to_plot)=="nls"){
    if(!nzchar(system.file(package = "mvtnorm"))) install.packages("mvtnorm")
    for(i in 1:500){
      if(i==1) nls_pred <- c()
      params <- drop(mvtnorm::rmvnorm(1,coef(fit_to_plot),
                                      sigma=vcov(fit_to_plot)))
      nls_pred <- cbind(nls_pred,predict(fit_to_plot,params))
    }
    nls_pred <- t(apply(nls_pred,1,quantile,probs = c(0.025, 0.975)))
    nls_pred <- as.data.frame(cbind(fit=predict(fit_to_plot),nls_pred)) 
    mod_pred <- nls_pred
    names(mod_pred) <- c("fit","lwr","upr")
  } else if(class(fit_to_plot)=="lm"){
    mod_pred <- data.frame(predict(lm_fit, interval = "confidence"))
  }
  return(mod_pred)
}

mod_pred_ci <- get_pred_ci(fit_to_plot)

Then we plot

plot1 +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=mod_pred_ci$lwr, ymax=mod_pred_ci$upr), fill="lightblue",alpha=0.5) +
  geom_line(aes(y=mod_pred_ci$fit),col="blue",lwd=1)
